1 unit Green Bell Pepper
6 tablespoon Sour Cream
1 cup Cheddar Cheese
1 cup White Rice
2 tablespoon Fajita Spice Blend
2 unit Black Beans
2 unit Lime
12 unit Flour Tortillas
20 ounce Ground Pork
2 unit Scallions
1 unit Tex-Mex Paste
½ cup Mexican Cheese Blend
Sugar
Cooking Oil
Salt
Pepper

• Adjust rack to middle position and
preheat oven to 425 degrees.
• In a medium pot (large pot for
8 servings), combine rice, 11⁄2 cups
water (21⁄2 cups for 8), and a pinch of
salt. Bring to a boil, then cover and
reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice
is tender, 18-20 minutes.
• Keep covered off heat until ready to
use in Step 6.

• While rice cooks, wash and dry
produce.
• Halve, deseed, and thinly slice bell
pepper crosswise into strips. Trim and
thinly slice scallions, separating whites
from greens. Zest one lime and quarter
both (zest two limes and quarter all
for 8 servings).
• In a small bowl, combine Tex-Mex
paste, 1⁄4 cup water, and 1 TBSP sugar
(1⁄2 cup water and 2 TBSP sugar for 8).

• Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over
medium-high heat. Add bell pepper
and cook, stirring, until softened and
slightly browned, 2 minutes.
• Add pork*, scallion whites, and Fajita
Spice Blend; season with salt and
pepper. Cook, breaking up meat
into pieces, until cooked through,
5-7 minutes.

• Meanwhile, drain beans (no need
to rinse!).
• Reduce heat under pan to medium
low. Add beans and Tex-Mex sauce to
pan. Stir to combine. Cover and cook
until liquid has slightly thickened,
2-3 minutes. Season with salt and
pepper. (For 8 servings, you may need
to cook pork and beans in batches.)

• Transfer pork and beans to an 8-by-8-
inch baking dish (9-by-13-inch baking
dish for 8 servings).
• Sprinkle with cheddar and Mexican
cheese blend. Bake, uncovered, on
middle rack until cheese is melted and
bubbly, 3-5 minutes.

• Meanwhile, wrap tortillas in damp
paper towels. Microwave until warm
and pliable, 30-60 seconds.
• Fluff rice with a fork; stir in lime zest
and juice from four lime wedges
(eight wedges for 8 servings). Taste
and season with salt and additional
lime juice if desired.
• Sprinkle cheesy pork and black bean
bake with scallion greens. Serve
family style with lime rice, tortillas,
sour cream, and remaining lime
wedges on the side.

***Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature
reaches 160°.***